Expected Points Modeling and its Applications to Team Performance

Will Hoover, J.P. Daliere, Roy Son

2025-10-12

Executive Report

The analysis of NBA shot attempt data is concerned with the following questions. How can team performance be quantified in terms of the shots they take? How can the expected points value for the shots teams take measure how teams are performing relative to their expectations? In this report, three statistical models were built using shot attempt data from the 2024-25 season to compute the probability of a successful shot attempt, as well as the expected point value for each shot. These models will be used to measure which teams over/under perform based on these expected values, where the best model will be selected based on quantitative and qualitative considerations.

The first model, known as Binning and Averaging, grouped shots by similar features such as location, distance, and shot type, then averaged the success rates within each group. While simple to implement, this approach could only generate predictions for groups of similar shots rather than for individual attempts.

The second model, Logistic Regression, advances by identifying mathematical relationships between shot features and the probability of success. It produces predictions between 0 and 1 for each shot, representing the likelihood that the shot will be made. This allows for more precise and flexible analysis compared to the group-based averaging approach.

The final model is the Random Forest, which estimates probabilities through hundreds of decision trees, each trained on different subsets of shot data. Each tree is trained on a random part of the data and predicts whether a shot will be made or missed. The final prediction combines all trees votes through majority vote, averaging predictions across trees to create individualized probabilities for each shot. This approach captures complex relationships that simpler models miss, such as how distance and shot type interact differently under various game conditions.

For each model, the expected points values were used to compute the expected value of teams outscoring their opponents, and these values were cross-referenced to that seasons NBA standings. Expected team results in wins based on their expected points were found to be quite varied, as the models estimated team performance either very accurately, or off by a significant margin, suggesting that shots alone may not quantify team performance. However, the models seemed to be able to distinguish which teams over and under performed, as models highlighted a trend between over performance and observed success.

Ultimately, the Random Forest model produced the most optimal statistical testing metrics as well as the closest approximations to NBA standings. Although the approach of aggregating the predicted points values at the season level as opposed to each individual game may be fundamentally limited, the accuracy and robustness of the Random Forest model provides a basis for evaluating performance at a more granular level. Additionally, its ability to most accurately forecast the expected points difference for each team suggests its use for identifying which teams are maximizing their shot quality and which may need strategic adjustments.

Technical Report

Question and Motivation:

In basketball, the simplest, most elementary goal of the game is to outscore the opposition, and of course the primary method of scoring is through field goal attempts. To win a game, a team simply needs to outscore the other team. Furthermore, it seems reasonable that good teams tend to outscore their opponents, or score more points than they allow their opponents to score for the whole season. Given this intuition, a natural question arises: How can individual level events such as field goal attempts be used to predict and quantify team performance? That is, how well does the expected points value of each field goal attempt per team translate into wins, and which teams are performing above and below expectations?

In this report, we will build three models to compute the probability that a player makes a field goal, and use these probabilities to compute expected points per shot for every field goal attempt in the data set. For each model, these expected points will be used to quantify and compare team performance across the league, both in terms of over and under performance, as well as how closely each model estimates the observed results. Using these results in accordance with statistical performance metrics and qualitative considerations, the best model for predicting and measuring team performance will be determined.

Data Construction and Cleaning

One of the premier tasks of a data scientist is properly cleaning, pre-processing, and preparing data before any form of advanced analysis can be performed. For this specific project, this proved to be the most challenging part of the project. This is primarily caused by the difficulty of extracting the shots data, was well as crucial missing information relating to free throws.

Free throws are a unique statistical anomaly of basketball, as a free throw is not a type of field goal attempt, even though a free throw can yield a score. Thus, this data wasnt included in the shot-tracking data. Data for free throws was nested inside a different data set, yet combining these two data sets wouldve proved to be a daunting task. Each set was produced by a different organization, and thus different identification codes for each player were present, as well as different formats of storing such data. Additionally, since free throws are quite different from a regular field goal attempt, including free throws in an expected points for field goals model would lead to disastrous interpret ability problems, and lead to a wide range of inaccuracies. Thus, it was decided to exclude free throws from consideration in each model, and attempt to quantify team performance and expected point differentials without them.

Here, we source the data from HoopRs commonallplayers package, and subsequently filter out players in the 2024-25 season and get their respective player ids. The main data frame is then built using rate limiting to extract all shots in the 24-25 season, as manual extraction of each shot yielded in an empty data frame. Note that these cells and several others in the report are set to eval = FALSE out due to the computation expense upon knitting, as well as the fact the data has already been extracted, processed, and saved to the local machine.

Model performance metrics are also defined. These metrics will be used for calculation purposes frequently in the report, while being employed as a method of comparing model selection much later. These metrics are defined here for reader comprehension and for code compiling purposes.

Missclassification Rate: This metric measures the proportion the model incorrectly predicts that a missed shot is made, and vice-versa.

\[ \textrm{MISS} = n^{-1}\sum_{i = 1}^{n}{\mathbb{I}(y_{i} \neq \mathbb{I}(\hat{p}_{i} \geq 0.5))},\]

Log-Loss: Log-Loss extends the idea of missclassifcation by punishing forecasts that are very wrong. For example, if the model predicts that the probability of a shot going in is 95%, but in reality the shot missed, then the penalty for missclassifying by a wide margin is wider. Models with lower log loss scores tend to make less extremely wrong predictions.

\[\textrm{LogLoss} = -1 \times \sum_{i = 1}^{n}{\left[ y_{i} \times \log(\hat{p}_{i}) + (1 - y_{i})\times\log(1-\hat{p}_{i})\right]}\] Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): RMSE measures how far away the models predictions are from the observed outcomes, by taking the average of squared residuals before taking the square root. The square both converts each residual into positive terms while also penalizing more extreme residuals.

\[RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}{(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}}{n}}\]

misclass <- function(y, phat){
  return( mean( (y != 1*(phat >= 0.5))))
}

# Define log-loss to measure model accuracy
logloss = function(y, phat){
  
  if(any(phat < 1e-12)) phat[phat < 1e-12] <- 1e-12
  if(any(phat > 1-1e-12)) phat[phat > 1-1e-12] <- 1-1e-12
  return(-1 * mean( y * log(phat) + (1-y) * log(1-phat)))
}

# RMSE was not explicitly defined as a function, but manually computed when needed

Next, we will construct the statistical models to forecast the probability of a successful shot attempt.

Model 1: Naive Binning and Averaging

The first model applies a simple, probabilistic approach to computing expected points, known as Binning and Averaging. The model is a conditional probability, where the probability is binned and averaged over all shots corresponding to selected set of features in the data as follows.

\[\textrm{Expected Points}(\text{Made Shot}) = \mathbb{P}(\text{Made Shot} \mid X_1 = x_1, \ldots, X_n = x_n) \times \text{Shot Value}\]

Where \(X_1 = x_i, ..., X_n = x_n\) represents the specific feature values of the shot, and shot value can be either 2 or 3 depending on the location of the shot.

To evaluate team-level offensive efficiency, we implemented a Binning and Averaging model that estimates the expected point value of each shot based on distance and shot type. In shots_by_ft, observations missing SHOT_DISTANCE were filtered out, and a new variable distance_ft was created by flooring each shot distance to the nearest whole foot. Note that ft does not represent free throws, but distance in feet. This standardizes groupings by converting continuous distances into discrete one-foot intervals, making it possible to compare shots of similar difficulty.

In league_average, shots were grouped by distance_ft and SHOT_TYPE to calculate league-wide baseline metrics. The key variable, expected_points_league, measures how many points an average player would be expected to score per attempt from each shot category. This data set was then merged back into the shot-level data as scored_shots, assigning each shot an expected_goal value representing what a league-average player would score from that location.

Finally, in Expected_vs_Actual, expected values were aggregated at the team level to compare expected and actual total points. Residuals (actual points minus expected points) quantify each teams offensive over or under performance relative to league averages. Teams with positive residuals, such as the Phoenix Suns and Denver Nuggets, exceeded expectations through superior shooting efficiency, while teams with negative residuals, like the Toronto Raptors and Charlotte Hornets, under performed due to poor shooting efficiency. The expected points totals reveal shot quality: teams like the Atlanta Hawks generated high volumes of efficient shot opportunities, while teams like the Charlotte Hornets took more shots from inefficient locations.

Aside: Note that throughout the analysis for the Binning and Averaging method, several variables and data frames were renamed using terms such as 2.0, 1.1, or edited differently than other frames in the analysis. This was the result in discrepancies in working with the data on each members local device, and as such, certain adjustments were made so each part of the project could run smoothly on one file. Sincere apologies to any confused readers.

shots_by_ft = shots %>%
  filter(!is.na(SHOT_DISTANCE)) %>%
  mutate(distance_ft = floor(SHOT_DISTANCE))

shots_by_ft2.0 = shots_by_ft %>% mutate(team_abbreviation = TEAM_NAME)

league_average = shots_by_ft %>%
  group_by(distance_ft, SHOT_TYPE)%>%
  summarize(
    attempt_league = n(),
    made_shots_league = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    fg_percentage_league = attempt_league / made_shots_league, 
    expected_points_league = mean(Points_rule, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'distance_ft'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
scored_shots = shots_by_ft %>%
  left_join(league_average %>%
              select(distance_ft, SHOT_TYPE, expected_points_league),
            by = c("distance_ft", "SHOT_TYPE"))%>%
  mutate(expected_goal = expected_points_league)

Expected_vs_Actual = scored_shots %>%
  group_by(TEAM_NAME)%>%
  summarize(
    expected_points = sum(expected_goal, na.rm = TRUE),
    actual_points = sum(Points_rule, na.rm = TRUE),
    number_of_shots = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )%>%mutate(residual = actual_points - expected_points)


ggplot(Expected_vs_Actual,
       aes(x = reorder(TEAM_NAME, residual),
           y = residual,
           fill = residual > 0))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Residuals (Actual - Expected) by Team", x = "Team", y = "Residual Points")

ggplot(Expected_vs_Actual,

Defensive Evaluation

To evaluate team-level defensive efficiency, we applied the Binning and Averaging model from the defensive perspective. In shots_defense, we constructed a defensive dataset by identifying the defending team for each shot using HTM (Home Team) and VTM (Visiting Team) variables to create an Opponents variable. As with the offensive model, observations missing SHOT_DISTANCE were filtered out, and distance_ft was created by flooring distances to the nearest whole foot.

In league_average_defense, shots were grouped by distance_ft and SHOT_TYPE to compute league-wide defensive expectations. The variable expected_points_league measures how many points a league-average defense would allow per attempt from each shot category. This data set was merged back into scored_shots_defense, assigning each shot an expected_goal representing the expected points an average defense would allow from that location.

Finally, in Expected_vs_Actual_defense, values were aggregated by defending team to compare expected and actual points allowed. Residuals (actual_points_allowed minus expected_points_allowed) quantify defensive over or underperformance. Teams with positive residuals, such as the Utah Jazz and Sacramento Kings, allowed more points than expected due to poor defensive execution, while teams with negative residuals, like the Oklahoma City Thunder and Cleveland Cavaliers, allowed fewer points through elite defense. expected_points_allowed reveals shot quality conceded: teams like the Chicago Bulls allowed opponents to generate high-quality shot opportunities, while teams like the Orlando Magic forced opponents into low-quality attempts.

shots_defense = shots_2025_model1.1 %>%
  select(GAME_ID, HTM, VTM, PLAYER_NAME, TEAM_NAME, SHOT_DISTANCE, SHOT_TYPE,
         SHOT_ZONE_BASIC, SHOT_MADE_FLAG, PTS)%>%
  mutate(
    SHOT_DISTANCE = as.numeric(SHOT_DISTANCE),
    Points_rule = case_when(
      SHOT_MADE_FLAG == 1 & SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3,
      SHOT_MADE_FLAG == 1 & SHOT_TYPE == "2PT Field Goal" ~ 2,
      TRUE ~ 0
         ),
    team_abbreviation = Team_abbreviation[TEAM_NAME],
    Opponents = case_when(
      team_abbreviation == HTM ~ VTM,
      team_abbreviation == VTM ~ HTM,
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ))

shots_by_ft_defense = shots_defense%>%
  filter(!is.na(SHOT_DISTANCE))%>%
  mutate(distance_ft = floor(SHOT_DISTANCE))

league_average_defense = shots_by_ft_defense %>%
  group_by(distance_ft, SHOT_TYPE)%>%
  summarize(
    attempt_league = n(),
    made_shots_league = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    fg_percentage_league = attempt_league / made_shots_league, 
    expected_points_league = mean(Points_rule, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

## `.groups` argument.
scored_shots_defense = shots_by_ft_defense %>%
  left_join(league_average_defense %>%
              select(distance_ft, SHOT_TYPE, expected_points_league),
            by = c("distance_ft","SHOT_TYPE")) %>%
  mutate(expected_goal = expected_points_league)

Expected_vs_Actual_defense = scored_shots_defense %>%
  group_by(Opponents)%>%
  summarize(
    expected_points_allowed = sum(expected_goal, na.rm = TRUE),
    actual_points_allowed = sum(Points_rule, na.rm = TRUE),
    number_of_shots_faced = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )%>% mutate(residuals_allowed = actual_points_allowed - expected_points_allowed )

Applications via Pythagorean Expectation

To extend the analysis from expected scoring efficiency to season-level performance, we implemented the Pythagorean Win Expectation model. This model operates on the principle that teams who score more points and allow fewer points tend to win more games, with the ratio of points scored to points allowed providing a strong predictor of overall success.

We began by constructing three data sets: Expected_Offense contains each teams total expected points scored, Expected_Defense contains total expected points allowed (both from the Binning and Averaging model), and Games_per_team accounts for the number of games each team played. These data sets were merged by team to form Pythagorean_win. We applied the Pythagorean Win formula used by Baseball Reference, calculating win percentage as:

\[\text{Win %} = \frac{PS^{1.83}}{PS^{1.83} + PA^{1.83}}\] Where PS represents points scored, and PA represents points allowed.

Results were rounded to whole numbers for the sake of interpretability. The Pythagorean Win projections aligned closely with the Expected Net Points analysis from the combined offense and defense models. Teams like the Oklahoma City Thunder and Houston Rockets, who ranked first and second in expected net points, also projected approximately 46 expected wins in the Pythagorean model. This consistency confirms that net shot quality measured by the Binning and Averaging model translates meaningfully into expected success over an 82-game season. Teams generating more efficient scoring opportunities while preventing opponents from doing the same naturally project higher win totals.

  select(TEAM_NAME, expected_points_scored = expected_points)

Expected_Defense = Expected_vs_Actual_defense %>%
  select(Opponents, expected_points_allowed) %>% rename(TEAM_NAME = Opponents)

Games_per_team = shots_2025 %>%
  select(TEAM_NAME, GAME_ID) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  count(TEAM_NAME, name = "games")

pythagorean_win = Expected_Offense %>%
  left_join(Expected_Defense, by = "TEAM_NAME") %>%
  left_join(Games_per_team, by = "TEAM_NAME") %>%
  mutate(
    expected_points = expected_points_scored / games,
    expected_points_against = expected_points_allowed / games,
    pythagorean_win_percentage = (expected_points^1.83) /
      ((expected_points^1.83) + (expected_points_against^1.83)),
    expected_wins = pythagorean_win_percentage * games,
    expected_losses = games - expected_wins
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    expected_wins = round(expected_wins),
    expected_losses = round(expected_losses)
  )

Model Performance

To assess how well the Pythagorean Win Expectation model aligned with actual team outcomes, we evaluated its predictive accuracy using the aforementioned Log Loss metric. This measure quantifies the distance between predicted probabilities and true binary outcomes, with lower values indicating higher accuracy. Log Loss penalizes incorrect predictions more heavily, making it particularly useful for evaluating probabilistic forecasts.

The evaluation began by joining predicted win probabilities from the Pythagorean model with true win percentages from official 2025 NBA standings to create Comparison. To simulate how the models probabilities would behave across a full season, we defined a function simulate_score() that expanded team-level probabilities into individual simulated games (82 games per team), used rbinom() to generate random win/loss outcomes based on true win probabilities, and calculated Log Loss errors using each teams predicted win probability. These errors were then averaged across all simulated games. To reduce variability, we repeated this process three times and averaged the results.

The model showed a mean Log Loss of 0.683, suggesting that the Pythagorean model using Binning and Averaging provides a reasonable approximation of team success but lacks precision compared to more sophisticated statistical models. The results confirm that scoring and defending efficiencies meaningfully translate into season-level successteams like the Oklahoma City Thunder and Houston Rockets ranked among the top in both predicted and actual win percentages. However, the models limitations reflect missing contextual factors such as free throws, player skill variations, and possession differences, as well as the Binning models inherent simplicity and inability to capture nonlinear relationships or interactions between variables like offense and defense.

simulate_score = function(df, games_per_team = 82){
  game_level = df %>%
    tidyr::uncount(games_per_team) %>%
    mutate(actual = rbinom(n(), size = 1, prob = true_win_percentage),
           prediction = pmin(pmax(predicted_win_percentage, 1e-12),1-1e-12),
           each_log_loss = -(actual * log(prediction)+(1-actual)* log(1-prediction))
           )
  tibble(mean_log_loss = mean(game_level$each_log_loss))}

results = bind_rows(
  simulate_score(Comparison),
  simulate_score(Comparison),
  simulate_score(Comparison))

results %>% summarize(average_log_loss = mean(mean_log_loss))

Model 2: Logistic Regression

A glaring issue with the naive binning and average model is that it can make estimates on small samples of data. This often occurs when the model uses continuous variables. Additionally, the Naive model bucketizes its outcomes; i.e.it cannot make a definitive prediction for each individual shot, only shots of similar features.

In this scenario, a logistic regression model is a good alternative. This is because logistic regression models are fit to the data and can make reasonable estimates for the relationships between continuous variables and the response variable.

Logistic Model Expression:

\[ \log\left(\frac{\mathbb{P}(Y= 1 \vert \boldsymbol{\mathbf{X}})}{\mathbb{P}(Y = 0 \vert \boldsymbol{\mathbf{X}})}\right) = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}X_{1} + \cdots + \beta_{p}X_{p}.\]

  • Binary Outcome Y (Probability of a shot being made, 1 indicated the shot was made, 0 a miss)

  • Variables \(X_1, ..., X_p\)

Our Logistic Model:

Our logistic model is modeling the probability that a shot results in a made basket. It is accounting for several continuous and categorical variables. One nice aspect of the logistic regression model which we laid out above is that it can account for continuous variables. This allows us to add some very important predictors into our model including location (x,y coordinate of the shot) and time (the time remaining in the quarter and the game). We expect intuitively that accounting for these variables will make our model more accurate. Lets see if this is the case!

For reference, these are the 13 variables used in our model:

  1. Location X (X-coordinate of the shot); continuous
  2. Location Y (Y-coordinate of the shot); continuous
  3. Shot Distance (ft away from the basket); continuous
  4. Action Type (specific type of shot); categorical
  5. Shot Zone Basic (zone of the court where a shot was taken); categorical
  6. Shot Zone Area (area of the court where a shot was taken); categorical
  7. Shot Zone Range (ft range away from the basket); categorical
  8. Shot Type (2-pointer or 3-pointer); categorical
  9. Period (quarter of the game (1-4)); categorical
  10. Minutes Remaining (minutes on the clock); continuous
  11. Seconds Remaining (seconds on the clock); continuous
  12. Quarter Time Left (time remaining in the quarter (in seconds)); continuous
  13. Game Time Left (time (in seconds) remaining in the game); continuous

Selected variables were also represented as factors as pre-processing, as the logistic regression model must interpret the different verbal entries for certain columns as numbers.

shots_2025_model2 <- shots_2025 %>%

Building the Logistic Model

To build our logistic model, we used the glm() function in R. This allowed us to fit a logistic linear model to the data.

After training our model, we used it to estimate the probability that a shot results in a made basket. We made predictions for every field goal attempted in the 2024-25 season. These predictions were made with the help of Rs predict function and were loaded into a vector which we added to our main shots data frame.

# n_sims was reduced from 100, as 100 was far too slow and took up too much memory due to the size of the data set
n_sims2 <- 2

## Initialize training and testing log loss vectors
train_logloss2 <- rep(NA, times = n_sims2)
test_logloss2 <- rep(NA, times = n_sims2)

## Set our training df to be 75% of the full df
n_row2 <- nrow(shots_2025_model2)
n_train2 <- floor(0.75 * n_row2)

## Create training-testing splits
for(r in 1:n_sims2){
  set.seed(479 + r)
  
  train_data2 <- shots_2025_model2 |> dplyr::slice_sample(n = n_train2)
  test_data2 <- shots_2025_model2 |> dplyr::anti_join(y = train_data2, by = "SHOT_ID")
  
  fit2 <- glm(
    formula = SHOT_MADE_FLAG ~ PERIOD + MINUTES_REMAINING + SECONDS_REMAINING + QUARTER_TIME_LEFT + GAME_TIME_LEFT + ACTION_TYPE + SHOT_TYPE + SHOT_ZONE_RANGE + SHOT_ZONE_AREA + SHOT_ZONE_BASIC + SHOT_DISTANCE + LOC_X + LOC_Y,
    data = train_data2,
    family = binomial("logit")
  )
  
  ## Predict probabilities
  train_preds2 <- suppressWarnings(predict(object = fit2, newdata = train_data2, type = "response"))
  test_preds2 <- suppressWarnings(predict(object = fit2, newdata = test_data2, type = "response"))
  train_preds2_log = train_preds2
  test_preds2_log = test_preds2
  
  ## Convert probabilities to expected points
  train_data2$train_probs2 <- train_preds2
  train_data2 <- train_data2 %>% mutate(EXPECTED_POINTS2 = train_preds2 * POSSIBLE_POINTS)
  
  test_data2$test_probs2 <- test_preds2
  test_data2 <- test_data2 %>% mutate(EXPECTED_POINTS2 = test_preds2 * POSSIBLE_POINTS)
  
  ## Compute log loss
  train_logloss2[r] <- logloss(train_data2$SHOT_MADE_FLAG, train_preds2_log)
  test_logloss2[r] <- logloss(test_data2$SHOT_MADE_FLAG, test_preds2_log)
}
## Print average log loss
cat("Logistic Regression Training Logloss:", round(mean(train_logloss2), digits = 3), "\n")

cat("Logistic Regression T Logloss:", round(mean(test_logloss2), digits = 3), "\n")

## Append predictions and compute expected points

Building the Expected Points Model:

After assigning a probability to every field goal in the dataframe, we are ready to build an expected points model. Our expected points predictions for each shot is simply computed by multiplying the probability (that the shot is made) by the amount of points the shot is worth.

\[E[X_i] = p_i \times Z_i\]

where

  • \(X_i\); \(i = 1, 2, ..., n\) is the amount of points scored from the \(i\)th shot
  • \(p_i\); \(i = 1, 2, ..., n\) is the probability that the \(i\)th shot is made
  • \(Z_i\); \(i = 1, 2, ..., n\) is the number of points the \(i\)th shot is worth

For example, a 2 point field goal attempt with a 50% probability of going in the basket has an expected points of 1.

shots_2025_xp2 <- shots_2025_model2 %>%
  mutate(EXPECTED_PROBABILITY = probability_preds2) %>%
  mutate(EXPECTED_POINTS = EXPECTED_PROBABILITY * POSSIBLE_POINTS)

This was done via a group_by > summarize command to group shots according to the team the shot-taker was playing for and against. We created two intermediate tables (one for expected points scored and one for expected points allowed) and then merged them into a combined data frame.

Assessing Model Accuracy

Lastly, we assess the accuracy of our logistic regression model.

We use log-loss to assess our models accuracy at predicting probabilities of shots being made. To compute log-loss, we first defined an intermediate function in R. Then, we created 2 training-testing splits (75%/25% training-test split). For each split, we trained the model using the training data and made predictions on the testing data. We then computed log-loss on the training and testing sets and averaged the estimates over the two splits. These values will be of greater importance when comparing performance between models later in the analysis.

cat("Model 2 Training Logloss:", round(mean(train_logloss2), digits = 3), "\n")
## Model 2 Training Logloss: 0.641

Model 3: Random Forests and Feature Analysis

A natural question concerning the evaluation of high-dimensional, complex data is how the many features interact with each other. While it seems natural to keep fitting logistic regression models, it becomes incredibly complex to specify these interactions between continuous, discrete, and categorical factors. Random Forest models simplify these calculations by representing these interactions as an ensemble of randomized regression trees, hence making a forest. The predictive results from these trees are then averaged to produce a probabilistic result. Fitting a random forest model for this particular data set is particularly complex, with the primary reason being the sheer size of the data. 204,316 field goal attempts were recorded in the 2024-25 NBA season, and running the typical 100 train/test splits yielded in memory overload. Thus, the model was trained on a single train/test split, which may yield in over fitting and bias. However, since Random Forest models are known for their ability to reduce over fit, and given that the data set is so large, this problem could be understated.

Pre-Processing

Several pre-processing steps were taken, which are listed in detail in the following chunks. The same variables were employed in the Random Forest model as in the Logistic Regression Model.

# eval = FALSE to save memory when knit, variables are loaded
n = nrow(shots_2025)
n_train = floor(0.75 * n) 
n_test = n - n_train

vars = c("PTS", "PERIOD", "MINUTES_REMAINING", "SECONDS_REMAINING", 
         "QUARTER_TIME_LEFT", "GAME_TIME_LEFT", "ACTION_TYPE", "SHOT_TYPE", 
         "SHOT_ZONE_BASIC", "SHOT_ZONE_AREA", "SHOT_ZONE_RANGE", 
         "SHOT_DISTANCE", "LOC_X", "LOC_Y")

shots_2025_forest = shots_2025 %>% mutate(
  ACTION_TYPE = factor(ACTION_TYPE), # factor columns numerically since this is a classification problem
  SHOT_TYPE = factor(SHOT_TYPE),
  SHOT_ZONE_BASIC = factor(SHOT_ZONE_BASIC),
  SHOT_ZONE_AREA = factor(SHOT_ZONE_AREA),
  SHOT_ZONE_RANGE = factor(SHOT_ZONE_RANGE),
  MADE = factor(ifelse(PTS > 0, 1, 0), levels = c(0, 1))
)

Fitting the Model

The Model was then trained and fit on the data, while log loss was recorded to measure statistical accuracy.

# eval = FALSE to save memory when knit, variables are loaded

# n_runs was reduced from 100, as 100 was far too slow and took up too much memory due to the size of the data set
n_runs = 1  
train_logloss <- rep(NA, times = n_runs)
test_logloss <- rep(NA, times = n_runs)

for (r in 1:n_runs){
  set.seed(479+r)
  
  # Split data
  train_data = 
    shots_2025_forest %>% 
    slice_sample(n = n_train) %>% 
    dplyr::select(dplyr::all_of(c("row_id", vars, "MADE")))
  
  test_data = 
    shots_2025_forest %>% 
    anti_join(y = train_data, by = "row_id") %>% 
    dplyr::select(dplyr::all_of(c("row_id", vars, "MADE")))
  
  # Extract actual values (0 = miss, 1 = made)
  made_train = as.numeric(as.character(train_data$MADE))
  made_test = as.numeric(as.character(test_data$MADE))
  
  # Remove row_id and PTS from training data
  train_data = train_data %>% select(-row_id, -PTS)
  test_data = test_data %>% select(-row_id, -PTS)
  
  # Fit random forest
  fit = ranger::ranger(
    formula = MADE ~ .,
    data = train_data, 
    probability = TRUE,
    importance = "permutation")
  
  # Get predictions (probability of made shot)
  train_preds = predict(object = fit, data = train_data)$predictions[,2]
  test_preds = predict(object = fit, data = test_data)$predictions[,2]
  
  # Calculate log loss
  train_logloss[r] = logloss(made_train, train_preds)
  test_logloss[r] = logloss(made_test, test_preds)
  
  full_data = shots_2025_forest %>% select(-row_id, -PTS)
  
  # Apply model to entire data set
  full_data_predictions = predict(object = fit, data = full_data)$predictions[,2]
  
  # Produce data set with probabilities and if the shot was made
  shots_2025_with_predicted_shots = shots_2025 %>% mutate(
    PREDICTED_PROB_MADE = full_data_predictions,
    PREDICTED_MADE = ifelse(full_data_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0),
  )
}
# Load all the saved RF model results to run computations on local machine to save memory, not a necessary step if compiling for the first time

shots_2025_with_predicted_shots <- readRDS("shots_2025_with_predicted_shots.rds")
fit <- readRDS("rf_model.rds")
train_logloss <- readRDS("train_logloss.rds")
test_logloss <- readRDS("test_logloss.rds")

The data was then given appropriate values for expected points, equivalent to the predicted probability of the shot resulting in a success, multiplied by the value of the attempted shot.

shots_2025_with_predicted_shots = shots_2025_with_predicted_shots %>%  mutate(EXPECTED_POINTS = case_when(
  SHOT_TYPE == "2PT Field Goal" ~ PREDICTED_PROB_MADE * 2, 
  SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ PREDICTED_PROB_MADE * 3,
  TRUE ~ 0
))

Here we evaluate the importance of each feature in the Random Forest Model. The selected method of quantifying feature importance is known as permutation importance, which quantifies the impact of a particular feature by measuring how much the models score drops when that features values are shuffled randomly. For example, the importance plot shows shot distance as the most important of the features, meaning that when the shot distances are shuffled, the model predicts probabilities far less accurately.

importance = fit$variable.importance
importance_frame = data.frame(
  Variable = names(importance),
  Importance = as.numeric(importance)
)
ggplot(importance_frame, aes(x = reorder(Variable, Importance), y = Importance)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + labs(x = "Feature Importance", y = "Variable")

Limitations and Future Considerations

Although these models seem to track well with observed values, there are several considerable limitations that affect the potential output and applicability of the models.

The foremost limitation of the model is the lack free throw data. For the 2024-25 season, a significant 13.9% of all points scored came from free throws. Although the Pythagorean Expectation attempts to remedy this lack of data, this statistic still fundamentally attempts to estimate outcomes where a significant part of that outcome is dependent on data we dont have. Thus, we must not extend these results too far, as some teams score a higher percentage of their points as free throws than others, affecting expected points and therefore expected win values.

The method of comparing NBA Season totals to the expected difference in points scored and allowed may also be a flawed metric, especially when a method for computing expected wins at the game by game level exists. However this consideration can be set aside on the basis that free throws often decide individual games, yet another reason why including free throw data would prove useful.

Another consideration to be made is the amount of spits performed on the data set, as only a few validation splits could potentially lead to model bias and, However, given the enormous raw size of the data set, as well as there being an ample amount of shot data for each specific combination of shot, this problem is potentially less significant than it may seem.

A final consideration when evaluating the efficacy of the previous models is a potential of important features that could contribute to expected points per shot. Consider the StatsBombR XG models from lecture, and variables such as the number of defenders between the goalpost, the angle to the goal, and the number of defenders near the shooter. This same logic is easily extended to basketball shot data, as the following features could potentially have an impact on expected points.

  1. Number (if any) of defenders contesting the shot attempt
  2. Distance of defenders hand to ball release point
  3. Time Remaining on Shot Clock
  4. Angle of shooter to basket on jump shots
  5. Score Differential

For example, the models may not be able to differentiate between a wide-open 25 foot three point shot with 15 seconds left on the shot clock compared to an attempt covered by two players with 0.5 seconds on the clock. These predictors would likely produce tighter estimates of the true expected points value, and if they were included in the model, its much more likely that teams that take shots associated with the good values of these categories would see a higher cumulative expected points total.

Conclusions

Ultimately, the Random Forest Model proved to be the most efficient and practical model for modeling expected points, producing the lowest misclassification rate (0.149), log-loss (0.401), and shot-level RMSE (261.154) across all performance tests, as illustrated in the table below.

model_stats <- tribble(
  ~Model, ~"Standings RMSE", ~"Misclass Rate", ~"Shot RMSE", ~"Training Logloss",
  "Model 1", 8.862, 0.377, 295.096, 0.683,
  "Model 2", 8.641, 0.374, 278.310, 0.641,
  "Model 3", 8.149, 0.149, 261.154, 0.401
)
model_stats = as.data.frame(model_stats)
model_stats
##     Model Standings RMSE Misclass Rate Shot RMSE Training Logloss
## 1 Model 1          8.862         0.377   295.096            0.683
## 2 Model 2          8.641         0.374   278.310            0.641
## 3 Model 3          8.149         0.149   261.154            0.401

Fundamentally, the Random Forest Model has inherent advantages over Logistic Regression due to its ability to capture high-order interactions between shot features. Its true power is exemplified in the consistency of point differential predictions per team, while residuals between expected and actual performance correlating moderately (r = 0.567) with observed NBA standings.

However, these results must be interpreted with appropriate caution. Each model assumes uniform player ability, meaning a 25-foot three-pointer receives the same predicted probability regardless of whether Stephen Curry or DeAndre Jordan attempts it. This limitation reveals an important insight: teams who consistently outperform expectations may be generating higher-quality looks for their best shooters, while underperforming teams may be taking lower-percentage shots even when accounting for game context.

Additionally, the absence of free throw datarepresenting approximately 14% of NBA scoringfundamentally limits the models ability to fully explain team success. The Random Forest models standings RMSE of 8.149 indicates that ranking predictions still deviate substantially from actual results, confirming that factors beyond shot quality (such as free throw efficiency, turnovers, and defensive intensity) significantly impact wins.

Future work should incorporate player-specific shooting profiles, defender proximity metrics, shot clock pressure, and free throw data. A game-by-game approach would also better compute win and team rank estimates, while also capturing game specific adjustments. In sum, the results of these models prove what has been at the forefront of the modern basketball revolution; if you want to win basketball games, take quality shots with high expected value.
